**ExpandableText** detects when content is truncated and shows an expand/collapse button. It supports two orthogonal axes: truncation direction (horizontal or vertical) and expansion mode (inline or dialog).

<%= embed OpPrimer::ExpandableTextComponentPreview, :default %>

## Anatomy

The component is a flex container with two children:

- **Truncation wrapper** — either `Primer::Beta::Truncate` (horizontal, single-line CSS ellipsis) or `OpPrimer::VerticalTruncateComponent` (vertical, multi-line `-webkit-line-clamp` via `.op-vertical-truncate`)
- **Expander button** — a `Primer::Alpha::HiddenTextExpander`, initially hidden, shown by the private `expandable-text` Stimulus controller when overflow is detected

## Two axes

### Truncation direction

| Mode | CSS mechanism | Use case |
|------|--------------|----------|
| `horizontal` (default) | `text-overflow: ellipsis` via Primer Truncate | Single-line labels in table cells, list items |
| `vertical` | `-webkit-line-clamp` via `OpPrimer::VerticalTruncateComponent` (`.op-vertical-truncate--lines-N`) | Multi-line descriptions, rich text previews |

### Expansion mode

| Mode | Behaviour | Use case |
|------|-----------|----------|
| `expansion: :inline` (default) | Clicking the expander toggles the text in place | Permission names, status labels |
| `expansion: :external` | Expander button triggers an external action (e.g. opening a dialog) | Long-form project attributes with formatted content |

All four combinations are valid.

## Used in

- **Administration > Users and permissions > Permissions report** — horizontal inline (permission names in table cells)
- **Administration > Work packages > Edit workflow** — horizontal inline (status names)
- **Project attributes** — vertical dialog (via `AttributeComponent`, which composes `ExpandableTextComponent`)

## Best practices

**Do**

- Always place the component inside a width-constrained parent so truncation can trigger
- Pass `flex: 1` when using inside a flex container to allow the truncation wrapper to shrink
- Use the component even for text that might not truncate — the expander stays hidden when content fits

**Don't**

- Don't set a fixed width on the component itself — constrain the parent container
- Don't use horizontal mode for multi-line content — use `direction: :vertical` with a `lines:` count

